@martinvw Afaik the compiler makes sure that this is the way to make sure that you can safely access a field as nonnull after an if - it only works if it is the very next line after the if.

What a feature, I can imagine that it fixes a lot of broken code, but is it part of the JDK/JRE specs or an implementation detail for specific JDK/JRE's?
And yes I tested it. Even adding a System.out.print() above it breaks it 😄

@kaikreuzer I did some more tests it's not true, my first tests give false positives because of context switching, but technically this should be the scenario you describe:
class Scratch {
    private static String field = null;
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        for (int i = 0; i < 10_002; i++) {
            new Thread(new Test()).start();
        }
    }

    static class Test implements Runnable {
        @Override
        public void run() {
            while (true) {
                field = "";

                try {
                    Thread.sleep(1);
                } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                    e.printStackTrace();
                }

                if (field != null) {
                    System.out.print("- " + field.length());
                }

                field = null;
            }
        }
    }
}
Without the Thread.sleep it does not give any NPE's but with it does most likely because it causes more context switches.

The correct code would be
                if (field != null) {
                    String localField = field;
                    System.out.print("- " + localField.length());
                }

